ution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Cheyne was born about 1370, in England, his father, Henry Cheney, was 26 and his mother, Joan Muschet, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter. He died on 30 December 1461, in Brackley, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 92."},"et":{"about 1370–30 December 1461":"umbes 1370–30. detsember 1461","1370–1399":"1370–1399","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1370–1461":"1370–1461","1390–1428":"1390–1428","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1344–1373":"1344–1373","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1373":"1373","1461":"1461","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1399":"1399","1364":"1364","1428":"1428","30 December 1461":"30. detsember 1461","Brackley, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley, Northamptonshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Fen Ditton, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1370–30 December 1461":"noin 1370–30. joulukuuta 1461","1370–1399":"1370–1399","1